				"uri": "/manual/hymns/a-poor-wayfaring-man-of-grief",
				"verses": [
					{
						"extra": false,
						"text": "A poor wayfaring Man of grief\nHath often crossed me on my way,\nWho sued so humbly for relief\nThat I could never answer nay.\nI had not pow&rsquo;r to ask his name,\nWhereto he went, or whence he came;\nYet there was something in his eye\nThat won my love; I knew not why.",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": false,
						"text": "Once, when my scanty meal was spread,\nHe entered; not a word he spake,\nJust perishing for want of bread.\nI gave him all; he blessed it, brake,\nAnd ate, but gave me part again.\nMine was an angel&rsquo;s portion then,\nFor while I fed with eager haste,\nThe crust was manna to my taste.",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": false,
						"text": "I spied him where a fountain burst\nClear from the rock; his strength was gone.\nThe heedless water mocked his thirst;\nHe heard it, saw it hurrying on.\nI ran and raised the suff&rsquo;rer up;\nThrice from the stream he drained my cup,\nDipped and returned it running o&rsquo;er;\nI drank and never thirsted more.",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": true,
						"text": "&rsquo;Twas night; the floods were out; it blew\nA winter hurricane aloof.\nI heard his voice abroad and flew\nTo bid him welcome to my roof.\nI warmed and clothed and cheered my guest\nAnd laid him on my couch to rest,\nThen made the earth my bed and seemed\nIn Eden&rsquo;s garden while I dreamed.",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": true,
						"text": "Stript, wounded, beaten nigh to death,\nI found him by the highway side.\nI roused his pulse, brought back his breath,\nRevived his spirit, and supplied\nWine, oil, refreshment&mdash;he was healed.\nI had myself a wound concealed,\nBut from that hour forgot the smart,\nAnd peace bound up my broken heart.",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": true,
						"text": "In pris&rsquo;n I saw him next, condemned\nTo meet a traitor&rsquo;s doom at morn.\nThe tide of lying tongues I stemmed,\nAnd honored him &rsquo;mid shame and scorn.\nMy friendship&rsquo;s utmost zeal to try,\nHe asked if I for him would die.\nThe flesh was weak; my blood ran chill,\nBut my free spirit cried, &ldquo;I will!&rdquo;",
						"type": "verse"
					},
					{
						"extra": true,
						"text": "Then in a moment to my view\nThe stranger started from disguise.\nThe tokens in his hands I knew;\nThe Savior stood before mine eyes.\nHe spake, and my poor name he named,\n&ldquo;Of me thou hast not been ashamed.\nThese deeds shall thy memorial be;\nFear not, thou didst them unto me.&rdquo;",
						"type": "verse"
					}
				]
